The Franchi SPAS-12 is a combat shotgun manufactured by Italian firearms company Franchi from 1979 to 2000. Only five percent (about 1,850) of the estimated SPAS-12 shotguns manufactured were imported into the U.S. The SPAS-12 is a dual-mode shotgun, adjustable for semi-automatic or pump-action operation. The SPAS-12 has been sold to military and police users worldwide,[1] on the civilian market, and has been featured in films and TV shows.

The appearance and intended purpose of the SPAS-12 initially led to its "combat" designation. Franchi renamed the model the Sporting Purpose Automatic Shotgun in 1990, after the importation ban of 1989 (when it was called the Special Purpose Automatic Shotgun). This allowed continued sales to the U.S. as a limited-magazine-capacity, fixed-stock model until 1994. Following the Federal Assault Weapons Ban, exports to the U.S. ceased. In September 2004 the ban expired, but Franchi had already ended production of the SPAS-12. [2]

title: For Sale:  Pair of Enfield Rifles - Near Perfect Shape, Super Collectible
postcontent:
For sale today is a pair of nearly perfect Enfields. I say nearly perfect because both have been taken out of the safe over the years to handle & admire. However I'd still rate both as 99%+ with respect to metal/wood finish plus the bores. 

The first is a Lithgow #1 Mark III. The stock has a beautiful reddish brown tone and metal is a deep dark black. You'll have to look with a magnifying glass to find any flaws. 

The second rifle is a #4 Mark II which makes it one of the last true Enfields to be built in the 1950's. This particular rifle can be traced to the so called Fazakerley "Irish Contract" order which of course was never fullfilled. 

The stock on the #4 is an unusual light blonde color with a yellow/brown tint. Metal is also a deep dark black and once again the overall package is nearly flawless. This rifle was actually still in it's original arsenal wrapping when I purchased it, but I couldn't resist looking. So I ended up taking it out. Looking back I probably should have left it factory wrapped because it would be worth several hundred dollars more, but hindsight is 20/20! 

As you can see from the pictures there are hundreds of dollars worth of accessories/ammo included with these rifles which are all absolutely original except for the canvas cases which are top quality reproductions, and the 1907 pattern bayonet for the #1 which is a Grade 1 collectors edition model from IMA. I decided on this bayonet for the #1 because I couldn't find an original that wasn't beat up and that wouldn't be a good match for this beautiful rifle. Both bayonets for the #4 are originals. 

Folks I realize that these are serious collector rifles so I'll be happy to arrange a time for any serious buyer to visit and inspect these. 

My asking price for the pair including all the ammo & accessories pictured is $2000. If you happen to have a nice GLOCK 34, SIG 522 rifle, GSG STG44-22, Beretta ARX, ISSC MK-22 rifle then I would consider making you a very fair partial trade allowance. These are the only firearms I'm really interested in right now.  

Rifles are to be picked up in the Brandon, FL area and you'll need to be a Florida resident who is at least 21 to purchase. 

Thanks for looking

I have a brand new in box and unfired Heckler & Koch P30 that I would like to sell/trade.

A recent HK pistol design, the P30 is a modern police and security pistol that combines function and safety. Ergonomic features include a special grip frame with interchangeable backstrap inserts and lateral plates, allowing the pistol to be individually adapted to any user. Ambidextrous controls include dual slide releases and magazine release levers.

Variants with a conventional double-action/single action trigger have a serrated decocking button located on the rear of the frame. Variants with HK’s enhanced double action only Law Enforcement Modification* (LEM) trigger have no external decocking controls.

The HK Law Enforcement Modification (LEM) trigger system combines the advantages of a cocked striker component (constant level of trigger pull from first to last round fired) with a double-action hammer system. Using such an enhanced trigger system consolidates ease of use and safety into a convenient, innovative trigger operation—one that reduces the chance of unintended firing. And in case of an ammunition-related failure to fire, all that is needed is an additional second or third squeeze of the trigger without the need of first pulling the slide back to re-cock the pistol. The enhanced LEM trigger system combines the reliability of a double action revolver trigger with the crisp trigger of a single action pistol.

P30S models have an ambidextrous safety lever mounted on both sides of the frame. S models are available in conventional double-action/single action trigger mode and with HK’s enhanced double action only Law Enforcement Modification trigger

A Picatinny rail molded into the front of the frame makes mounting lights, laser aimers, or other accessories easy and convenient. The extractor doubles as a loaded chamber indicator providing a subtle tactile and visual reminder of a loaded chamber.

Extensively tested, the P30 has already been adopted by several European police agencies. Excellent weight and balance make the P30 naturally pointable, easy to control, and accurate to shoot. An open notch rear sight with luminous (non-radioactive) contrast points allows for fast and accurate target acquisition, even under poor lighting conditions.

During a recent (2009-2010) endurance test, a P30 test pistol fired more than 91,000 rounds without any major component failures.

P30 and P30S models available in 9 mm and .40 S&W.
